---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    { "@type": "Question", "name": "What does AS 4970 actually require for protecting a kept tree on a Cardinia build site?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "AS 4970-2009 'Protection of trees on development sites' sets out four things in plain order: (1) calculate the Tree Protection Zone (TPZ) as 12 × the trunk diameter at 1.4m, with a minimum 2m radius and a maximum 15m; (2) calculate the Structural Root Zone (SRZ), a smaller inner zone using a formula based on trunk diameter that protects the structural roots holding the tree up; (3) fence the TPZ with a temporary protection fence at least 1.8m high, signed, before any site work starts; (4) impose 'no-go' rules inside the TPZ — no excavation, no soil change, no stockpiling, no vehicles, no concrete washout, no chemical storage. If you must enter the TPZ for genuine engineering reasons, a Project Arborist (AQF Level 5 minimum) must supervise and document each incursion. Cardinia Shire and most planning permits require an AS 4970 report at planning approval stage on any site retaining a significant tree." } },
    { "@type": "Question", "name": "What is the fencing spec — what does the TPZ fence actually have to look like?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Standard AS 4970 fencing spec: temporary steel mesh panels (the orange or green construction-grade panels, not domestic star pickets and bunting), 1.8m minimum height, secured at the base with concrete feet, panels overlapped and clipped at joins. Signage at every visible face: 'Tree Protection Zone — No Entry — Project Arborist (name + mobile).' Ground inside the TPZ kept at original grade — no fill, no cut, no compaction. We typically lay 100mm of woodchip mulch inside the TPZ before fencing goes up: it reduces compaction from accidental foot traffic, retains soil moisture, and absorbs minor knocks. Fencing stays up from site establishment until practical completion — not until 'we need to get a load in there.' If a section has to come down temporarily, written authorisation from the Project Arborist, supervised entry, fence back up at end of day." } },
    { "@type": "Question", "name": "What's the watering schedule for a kept tree during a Cardinia construction project?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Construction is a drought event for the kept tree even in a wet winter — the surrounding ground gets compacted, runoff patterns change, and the canopy often loses a percentage of feeder roots to inadvertent damage. Standard watering regime: 50mm of water per square metre of TPZ area, monthly through Apr–Sep (cooler months) and fortnightly through Oct–Mar (hotter months). Deep-soak via tree-ring soaker hose or 30-minute slow-flow sprinkler — not a quick blast that runs off. For a mature River Red Gum or Manna Gum with a 10m radius TPZ, that's roughly 15,000L per watering event during summer. Sounds like a lot. It is. But it's a fraction of the cost of replacing a 60-year-old tree that died because no one watered it through a 2-year build." } },
    { "@type": "Question", "name": "Who signs off the AS 4970 compliance at the end of a Cardinia build?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "The Project Arborist — the AQF Level 5 (or higher) consulting arborist named in the AS 4970 report at planning approval stage. They inspect at four standard milestones: pre-construction (TPZ fencing inspection, baseline tree health assessment, photos); during demolition / bulk earthworks; before major service trenching near the TPZ; and at practical completion (final tree health assessment, fence removal sign-off). Each inspection gets a written report with photos, lodged with Council if required by the permit condition. The sign-off matters: if the tree fails or declines in the 24 months after completion, the planning permit holder is exposed unless the Project Arborist documentation shows compliance throughout. We carry that AQF Level 5 capacity in-house, or we coordinate with the consulting arborist already named on your permit." } }
  ]
};
---
<Layout
  title="AS 4970 tree protection during Cardinia construction — TPZ fencing, watering, sign-off | (03) 9003 0108"
  description="What AS 4970-2009 requires for protecting a kept tree on a Cardinia Shire build site — Tree Protection Zone calculation, fencing spec, no-dig area, watering schedule, and Project Arborist sign-off at four milestones."
  canonical="https://cardiniatreeservices.com.au/as4970-protection-cardinia/">
  <Fragment slot="head">
    <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(faqSchema)} />
  </Fragment>

  <section class="hero">
    <div class="hero-inner">
      <span class="hero-eyebrow">Compliance &middot; AS 4970-2009 on Cardinia builds</span>
      <h1>AS 4970 tree protection on a <span class="accent">Cardinia construction site</span>.</h1>
      <p class="hero-sub">
        You&rsquo;re keeping the big Manna Gum in the corner of the block.
        The planning permit says you must. AS 4970-2009 sets out how:
        calculate the TPZ, fence it, no-dig inside it, water it through the
        build, and sign it off at four milestones. We write the report, run
        the fencing inspection, and certify compliance.
      </p>
      <div class="hero-actions">
        <a class="btn btn-primary" href="tel:+61390030108">&#9742; Call (03) 9003 0108</a>
        <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="/quote/">Get an AS 4970 quote</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <span class="section-eyebrow">What the standard says</span>
      <h2>The four pillars of AS 4970-2009 compliance.</h2>
      <div class="divider"></div>
      <div style="max-width: 65rem;">
        <p>
          AS 4970-2009 &ldquo;Protection of trees on development sites&rdquo;
          is the Australian Standard that Cardinia Shire planning permits
          point to when they say &ldquo;the existing tree shall be retained
          and protected throughout construction.&rdquo; The standard is
          short, sensible and almost always misunderstood by builders the
          first time they encounter it. Four pillars.
        </p>
        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Pillar 1. Calculate the TPZ.</h3>
        <p>
          The Tree Protection Zone is the circular area around the trunk
          inside which the tree&rsquo;s feeder roots and structural roots
          live. Formula: TPZ radius = 12 × Diameter at Breast Height (DBH,
          measured at 1.4m). Minimum 2m, maximum 15m. For a 60cm DBH mature
          River Red Gum that&rsquo;s a 7.2m radius circle &mdash; a 14.4m
          diameter no-build envelope. We mark the TPZ on the site plan in
          red, and we mark the Structural Root Zone (a smaller inner circle
          using a separate formula) in orange. Inside the SRZ is genuinely
          no-go &mdash; cutting structural roots can drop the tree.
        </p>
        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Pillar 2. Fence the TPZ.</h3>
        <p>
          1.8m steel mesh panels with concrete feet, signed at every visible
          face, up before site establishment, down only at practical
          completion. Mulch the ground inside the TPZ to 100mm before fencing
          to reduce compaction risk. Bunting and star pickets &mdash; the
          domestic shortcut &mdash; is not AS 4970 compliant and will get
          flagged by Council&rsquo;s building surveyor on a routine
          inspection.
        </p>
        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Pillar 3. No-dig inside the TPZ.</h3>
        <p>
          No excavation, no soil cut, no soil fill, no stockpiling of
          materials, no vehicle traffic, no concrete or chemical washout,
          no temporary site office, no portable toilet. If a service trench
          genuinely must enter the TPZ &mdash; sewer connection, stormwater,
          power conduit &mdash; AS 4970 allows it under three conditions:
          hand-dig only, supervised by the Project Arborist, with any root
          over 25mm preserved and re-buried (not cut). Air-spade excavation
          is the gold-standard method for these incursions and we carry one
          on the truck.
        </p>
        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Pillar 4. Water it through the build.</h3>
        <p>
          Construction is a drought event for the kept tree. Compaction
          reduces water infiltration even outside the TPZ. Runoff patterns
          change. Some feeder roots will be lost despite best efforts. The
          watering regime &mdash; deep-soak monthly cool season, fortnightly
          warm season &mdash; keeps the tree in stress range A rather than
          stress range C.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section section-alt">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <span class="section-eyebrow">Cardinia-specific notes</span>
      <h2>Why Cardinia AS 4970 jobs need extra care.</h2>
      <div class="divider"></div>
      <div style="max-width: 65rem;">
        <p>
          A few patterns we see repeatedly on Cardinia Shire AS 4970 work,
          worth flagging up front.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Indigenous-remnant species are usually the keepers.</strong>
          On growth-corridor subdivisions (Pakenham, Officer, Cardinia
          Lakes, Heritage Springs) the trees retained on individual lots
          are almost always the surviving River Red Gum, Yellow Box or
          Manna Gum that pre-date subdivision. These have been there since
          before the bulldozers. The root systems extend well beyond the
          obvious TPZ and have already adapted to the original landform &mdash;
          which means soil cuts and fills around them are particularly
          damaging.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>BAL bushfire overlay interaction.</strong> In the hills
          district (Beaconsfield Upper, Cockatoo, Emerald, Gembrook, parts
          of Avonsleigh) most building lots are in a Bushfire Management
          Overlay and have a BAL rating &mdash; commonly BAL-29 or BAL-40.
          Defendable space requirements can conflict with AS 4970 TPZ
          rules &mdash; the bushfire engineer wants the canopy reduced or
          the tree gone, the planning condition wants it kept. We work
          this conflict out with the bushfire engineer and the consulting
          arborist at planning stage so it doesn&rsquo;t turn into a stop-work
          order at frame stage.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Builder education up front.</strong> Most builders have
          done one or two AS 4970 jobs and learned the hard way. We do a
          15-minute toolbox talk at site establishment for every site
          worker who will be on the block during the build &mdash; concretor,
          plumber, electrician, framer. Five minutes saves a $200,000
          replacement liability later. We bring printed TPZ diagrams and
          stickers for the site shed.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <span class="section-eyebrow">Frequently asked</span>
      <h2>Cardinia AS 4970 questions.</h2>
      <div class="divider"></div>
      <div style="max-width: 65rem;">

        <h3>What does AS 4970 actually require?</h3>
        <p>
          Calculate the TPZ (12 × DBH, 2&ndash;15m range) and the SRZ.
          Fence the TPZ with 1.8m steel mesh, signed, before any site work.
          No excavation, fill, stockpile, traffic or washout inside the
          TPZ. Watering regime through the build. Project Arborist
          supervises any genuine incursion. Sign-off at four standard
          milestones.
        </p>

        <h3>What does the fence have to look like?</h3>
        <p>
          1.8m steel mesh panels with concrete feet, not domestic star
          pickets and bunting. Mulch the ground inside to 100mm before
          fencing. Up from site establishment, down at practical
          completion only.
        </p>

        <h3>What&rsquo;s the watering schedule?</h3>
        <p>
          50mm per square metre of TPZ, monthly Apr&ndash;Sep, fortnightly
          Oct&ndash;Mar. Deep-soak via soaker hose or slow-flow sprinkler.
          For a 10m TPZ that&rsquo;s about 15,000L per summer event &mdash;
          large, but small against the replacement cost of the tree.
        </p>

        <h3>Who signs the project off?</h3>
        <p>
          The Project Arborist (AQF Level 5 minimum) named in the AS 4970
          report. Four inspections: pre-construction, demolition/earthworks,
          service trenching, practical completion. Documentation lodged
          with Council if the permit conditions require it. We hold that
          AQF Level 5 capacity in-house.
        </p>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section section-cta">
    <div class="section-inner" style="text-align: center;">
      <h2>Got a planning permit with a tree retention condition?</h2>
      <p style="max-width: 50rem; margin: 1rem auto;">
        Send us the permit reference and the plans. We&rsquo;ll come back
        with the AS 4970 report, the TPZ fencing quote, the watering
        schedule and a fixed price for the four inspection milestones
        &mdash; all in one package.
      </p>
      <div class="hero-actions" style="justify-content: center;">
        <a class="btn btn-primary" href="tel:+61390030108">&#9742; Call (03) 9003 0108</a>
        <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="mailto:quotes@cardiniatreeservices.com.au">Email the permit</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
